INT. THE COMEDY BASEMENT - NIGHT

_Warm stage lights cut through darkness. The electricity of live performance._

A cramped basement comedy club. Exposed brick walls plastered with faded posters. Maybe 30 people scattered across mismatched chairs. The kind of room where dreams go to get heckled.

MAYA SANTOS (late 20s, African-American and Filipina, natural hair in a messy bun, thrift-store bomber jacket) stands in the spotlight. Microphone in hand. She's three minutes into her set.

The crowd is... mixed. Some laughs. Some phones. One guy asleep.

MAYA
(with sharp timing)
So I'm Black and Filipina, which means family gatherings are just... 
(beat)
...confusing. My tita makes the best lumpia, my grandma makes the best collard greens, and I'm in the corner like "Can someone please tell me which oppression to lead with?"

A few genuine laughs. Maya feeds off them.

MAYA (CONT'D)
People ask me "What are you?" Like I'm a PokÃ©mon. "Oh, you got the rare dual-type!" 
(does a PokÃ©mon voice)
"Maya used Survival Instinct! It's super effective!"

More laughs now. She's finding her rhythm.

MAYA (CONT'D)
I moved to Brooklyn thinking I'd finally find my people. You know what I found? A $2,400 studio apartment and a white guy with dreads who told me about "authentic" Filipino food. 
(beat)
Bro, you're from Connecticut.

The room erupts. She's got them now.

But Maya's eyes aren't on the laughing crowdâ€”they're scanning. Reading faces. Body language. Energy shifts. It's instinctive. Protective.

MAYA (CONT'D)
(softer, more honest)
Truth is, I've spent my whole life reading rooms. Figuring out which version of myself keeps me safe. 
(beat)
That's not a joke, by the way. That's just survival.

The laughter fades to something else. Recognition. Connection.

MAYA (CONT'D)
(grinning)
But hey, at least I can make you laugh about it, right?

Applause. Real applause. Maya soaks it in for exactly one second, thenâ€”

COMEDY CLUB EMCEE (O.S.)
Maya Santos, everybody! Give it up!

Maya waves, steps off stage. The house lights come up.

