A tiny studio in Brooklyn. Murphy bed half-folded. Walls covered with comedy show flyers, scribbled joke notes, and one framed photo: Young Maya with her parents, everyone smiling.

Maya sits on her bed, laptop open. Email inbox: 47 unread messages. She scrolls past them all to one:

> **SUBJECT:** Open Mic Spot Available - The Ivory Room

Her cursor hovers over it. Doesn't click.

She closes the laptop. Opens a notebook instead. Pages filled with jokes, crossed-out punchlines, margin notes in different colored pens.

She writes: _"What if I could stop hiding?"_

Stares at it.

Crosses it out.

Writes: _"What if hiding IS the joke?"_

Her phone buzzes. Text from MIRIAM (contact photo: beautiful Latina woman with glasses, mid-laugh):

> **MIRIAM:** "how'd it go tonight babe?"

Maya smiles. Types back:

> **MAYA:** "Killed. Fred said I should do The Ivory Room."

> **MIRIAM:** "OMG DO IT"

> **MAYA:** "I'm not ready"

> **MIRIAM:** "you've been 'not ready' for 3 years"
> **MIRIAM:** "im coming over"

MAYA
(out loud)
No, no, noâ€”

Three dots appear. Then disappear. Then reappear.

> **MIRIAM:** "too late already here"

A knock at the door.

Maya sighs, smiles despite herself, and opens it.

INT. MAYA'S APARTMENT - CONTINUOUS

MIRIAM (late 20s, openly bisexual, wearing an oversized cardigan and doc martens) bursts in carrying takeout bags.

MIRIAM
I brought emotional support dumplings.

MAYA
You were two blocks away when you texted, weren't you?

MIRIAM
I was downstairs.
(unpacking food)
